    <name>
      <text>Finding the Parabola with Given Focus and Directrix</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p> Find the parabola with focus \(F({@Focus_x@},{@Focus_y@})\) and directrix \( (l): y={@directrix@} \)</p>
<p>[[input:ans5]] [[validation:ans5]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt5]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked solution</h3>
<p>We want to find the parabola with focus \(F({@Focus_x@},{@Focus_y@})\) and directrix \( (l): y={@directrix@} \)</p>
<p>A parabola consists of the set of points \((x,y)\) which are <b>equidistant</b> from the focus and the directrix.
<br>So, for a general focus \(F(x_{0}, y_{0}+p)\) and directrix \((l): y = y_{0}-p\), we have</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">Distance to \(F\): &emsp; \(\sqrt{(x - x_0)^2 + (y - (y_0 + p))}\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">Distance to \((l)\): &emsp; \(y - (y_0 - p))\)</p>

<p>Therefore, the points on the parabola satisfy,</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\sqrt{(x - x_0)^2 + (y - (y_0 + p))^2} = y - (y_0 - p)\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow (x - x_0)^2 + (y - (y_0 + p))^2 = (y - (y_0 - p))^2)\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow (x - x_0)^2 + (y^2 - 2y(y_0 + p) + (y_0 + p)^2) = (y^2 - 2y(y_0 - p) + (y_0 - p)^2))\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow (x - x_0)^2 - 2y(y_0 + p) + (y_0^2 + 2y_0p + p^2) = - 2y(y_0 - p) + (y_0^2 - 2y_0p + p^2))\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow (x - x_0)^2 - 4yp + 4y_0p = 0\)</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow (x - x_0)^2 = 4p(y - y_0)\)</p>

<br>

<p>So in general, for focus \(F(x_{0}, y_{0}+p)\) and directrix \((l): y = y_{0}-p\), the corresponding parabola is,
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\((x-x_{0})^{2}= 4 p (y - y_{0}) \)</p>

<br>

<p>Then, for the focus and directrix given we have \(x_0 = {@Focus_x@}\), and,</p>

<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
y_{0} + p =  {@Focus_y@} \\
y_{0} - p =  {@directrix@}
\end{array}\right.
\hspace{10px} \Rightarrow \hspace{10px} y_{0} = {@expr6@}, \hspace{5px} p = {@expr8@}\)</p>

<br>

<p>Now substituting these values for \(x_{0}, y_{0}\) and \(p\) into the general formula, we conclude,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\({@expr_c@}\)
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\Rightarrow {@expr_c1@}\)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
